{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01XzzGC4Js37UUZu3n1kPi7P","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting! The pod is showing probe failures with \"Authentication failed\" errors. The events show:\n- Liveness probe failed 6 times\n- Readiness probe failed 12 times\n\nBut the override file `/etc/health/overrides/mongodb-replica-1` does NOT exist inside the pod (the file didn't get mounted). \n\nWait, but the ConfigMap `health-overrides` has key `mongodb-replica-1` with value `legacyHealthPass123`. And the volume mount is at `/etc/health/overrides`. So the file SHOULD exist at `/etc/health/overrides/mongodb-replica-1`.\nBut the cat command shows \"No such file or directory\". That's odd. Let me check what files are actually in that directory.\n\nActually, wait. Looking at the volume mounts, I see `health-secret` is mounted at `/etc/health` and `health-overrides` is mounted at `/etc/health/overrides`. In Kubernetes, when you mount a volume at a subdirectory path like that, there might be an issue with how the mounts are layering or conflicting.\n\nBut looking at the pod events more carefully, I'm seeing \"Readiness probe failed: MongoServerError: Authentication failed\" - so authentication is actually failing. Yet the pod status shows 1/1 Running, which seems contradictory. If the readiness probe is failing, shouldn't that be reflected differently?\n\nLet me think through the timing here. The pod is 6m45s old, and the readiness probe failures started around 5m42s ago. With an initialDelaySeconds of 60 and failureThreshold of 6, the probe should have marked the pod as not ready after 6 consecutive failures. But the current status still shows Ready. Either the pod recovered between when I ran the get command and when I ran describe, or there's something else going on with how the status is being reported.\n\nThe real issue seems to be that the override file isn't actually present inside the pod, so the health check script is falling back to the default password. But if it's using `healthpass123` from the secret, the authentication shouldn't be failing unless that password is wrong or the service isn't accepting it.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1665,"cache_read_input_tokens":33710,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1665},"output_tokens":36,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"dd902376-bb10-48c3-9a80-b3e6e214b17b","uuid":"858b0a82-06fa-4bf7-8b84-e66567a37c24","request_id":"req_011Cc5LQNDXtyRhwyJWcKXbh"}
