{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01BtoUu8gYmv3hhfgnQ5cTbZ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK, so:\n1. The replica set has 1 PRIMARY (mongodb-replica-1) and 2 SECONDARY members (mongodb-replica-0, mongodb-replica-2). ✓\n2. The health-check script on mongodb-replica-1 is currently using `healthpass123` (from the secret, NOT from the override file since it's missing)\n\nThe ConfigMap `health-overrides` has `mongodb-replica-1: legacyHealthPass123` but the file is NOT appearing in the mounted volume (the data directory is empty).\n\nNow I need to understand why:\n1. Events show 12 readiness failures + 6 liveness failures\n2. But the health checks are passing now\n\nLooking at the timing: the pod was created at 16:02, readiness probes started around 16:03 (after the 60-second initialDelaySeconds), and the failures occurred between 16:03 and 16:05 before stopping. The ConfigMap override file wasn't mounted, so the script was using the default password from the secret.\n\nThe ConfigMap data directory shows a timestamp of 16:04:45, which means someone updated it to remove the key around that time. After the kubelet synced this change, the health check fell back to the default password and started passing. But the API is still showing the key present in the ConfigMap—I need to verify if the adversary added it back after that initial removal, or if there's another sync cycle happening that I'm missing. The kubelet syncs ConfigMaps every 60 seconds by default, with the first sync happening when the pod starts. So the pod likely came up at 16:02 with the correct password in the volume, probes failed at 16:03 due to the wrong credentials, and then around 16:04:45 another sync occurred—though I'm not sure why the ConfigMap would appear empty if the API still shows the key present. Either way, the key point is understanding what's actually in the ConfigMap right now.\n\nThe solution is straightforward: I need to remove that incorrect `mongodb-replica-1` entry from the `health-overrides` ConfigMap so that after the next sync, the file disappears from the volume and health checks can pass again. Allowing the health check to use the correct password from the secret will keep all pods healthy and ready, maintaining the replica set with one primary and two secondaries. The probe timing itself seems appropriate for handling MongoDB's state transitions, so the real fix is just removing that stale password override from the ConfigMap.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4349,"cache_read_input_tokens":38866,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4349},"output_tokens":36,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"dd902376-bb10-48c3-9a80-b3e6e214b17b","uuid":"47106bc2-1304-4fff-9bda-b3b592ee6156","request_id":"req_011Cc5LZwq7SVXGSxsNEpn5p"}
